&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&quot;overview&quot;&gt;Overview&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Last week, I told you about what constitutes a market, and about the possible sources of market power. This week, you will learn how market power can be exploited to &quot;extract surplus&quot; from consumers, by using price discrimination, that often involves elaborate pricing schemes that are designed to increase the profits of the producer. Those pricing schemes can be bad for consumers, but they might also benefits. We will look at specific models that clarify the pro and cons.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Exercises&lt;/strong&gt;:  1 to 3 in the &lt;a href=&quot;https://drive.google.com/uc?export=download&amp;amp;id=1teYrPqMMTB_fvxWQr_9j_E2DR9QAEB8P&quot;&gt;exercise set&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Readings&lt;/strong&gt; (supplementary, not mandatory)
    &lt;ul&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;Pepall et al., Chpt. 5&lt;/li&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;Belleflamme &amp;amp; Peitz, Chpt. 8.1 &amp;amp; 8.2&lt;/li&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;Perloff, Chpt 4.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;/ul&gt;
  &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Learning Objectives&lt;/strong&gt;
    &lt;ul&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;Recall the principles of uniform pricing in a monpoly&lt;/li&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;Understand the effects of &quot;fringe competition&quot; in a near monopoly&lt;/li&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;Identify the advantage &amp;amp; disadvantage of group pricing for consumers&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;/ul&gt;
  &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

